%I A328292 #10 Jun 21 2026 05:54:21
%S A328292 9876543210,9876543210,9876543210,9876543120,9876543210,9876543210,
%T A328292 9876543201,9876543120,9876543210,9876543210,9876524130,9876543120,
%U A328292 9876542130,9876543012,9876543210,9876543120,9876543210,9876543210,9876543102,9876543120,9876543201
%N A328292 a(n) is the greatest nonnegative multiple of n with distinct decimal digits.
%C A328292 Similar sequence with "smallest" rather than "greatest" is A302096 (with A302096(100) = 0) or also A061604 (with A061604(100) = 12345678900). The first 99 terms of these two sequences coincide. See Ian Stewart reference. - _Bernard Schott_, Jun 21 2026
%D A328292 Ian Stewart, La chasse aux trésors mathématiques, problème 40 pp. 82 and 330, le test du onze, Flammarion, 2010.
%H A328292 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A328292/a328292.gp.txt">PARI program for A328292</a>
%F A328292 a(n) = n * A328291(n).
%F A328292 a(n) <= 9876543210 for any n > 0.
%F A328292 a(n) = 0 for any n > 9876543210.
%o A328292 (PARI) \\ See Links.
%Y A328292 Cf. A010784, A061604, A302096, A328291.
